Concerning interconnection among fixed network operators:  The incumbent’s charges for termination depend on which level of its network’s hierarchy the traffic is handed over. There is a local, a single and a double tandem charge for interconnection.  Generally, the interconnection charge of all other fixed network operators is the same as the single tandem charge of the incumbent regardless of their network’s structure. In cases however, where higher costs could be proved, the regulatory authority will take them (besides other parameters) into account in its decision.  Concerning mobile termination the regulatory authority decided to reach symmetric rates within a certain time.    .

When smaller operators are found to have SMP, they may be subject to “softer” obligations than strict cost orientation.    For the fixed interconnection markets it is only for termination that the smaller operators are found to have SMP. These are under an obligation to provide termination at “reasonable prices”. The concept of “reasonable prices” is reviewed separately.   Any resulting asymmetry will be the outcome of how “reasonable prices” is interpreted, rather than any intended policy choice.  .

When smaller operators are found to have SMP, they may be subject to “softer” obligations than strict cost orientation. For the fixed interconnection markets it is only for termination that the smaller operators are found to have SMP. These are under an obligation to provide termination at “reasonable prices”. The concept of “reasonable prices” is reviewed separately. Any resulting asymmetry will be the outcome of how “reasonable prices” is interpreted. The guideline is that only differences in underlying costs can legitimize differences in prices.

When smaller operators are found to have SMP, they may be subject to “softer” obligations than strict cost orientation. For the fixed interconnection markets it is only for termination that the smaller operators are found to have SMP. These are under an obligation to provide termination at “reasonable prices”. The concept of “reasonable prices” is reviewed separately. For termination the smaller operators must be able to document that they have a different cost base than the incumbent operator.   For termination on mobile networks NPT recognizes that symmetry is to be acheived in the medium term, but that asymmetric rates may be justifiable in the short term for a defined period of time in line with upcoming EC Recommendation on the regulatory treatment of fixed and mobile termination rates.

When smaller operators are found to have SMP, they may be subject to “softer” obligations than strict cost orientation. For the fixed interconnection markets it is only for termination that the smaller operators are found to have SMP. These are under an obligation to provide termination at “reasonable prices”. The concept of “reasonable prices” is reviewed separately. For termination the smaller operators must be able to document that they have a different cost base than the incumbent operator. So far, none of these operators have been able to document higher costs, so in practice the fixed termination rates are symmetric. For termination on mobile networks NPT recognizes that symmetry is to be acheived in the medium term, but that asymmetric rates may be justifiable in the short term for a defined period of time in line with EC Recommendation on the regulatory treatment of fixed and mobile termination rates.
